english:
  title: In Praise of the Elixir of Life
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I dreamed I soared up to heaven's court,
    Where the Jade Emperor summoned me near,
    Speaking with care as he gave me a gift—
    A luminous drug, glowing crimson and bright.

    I bowed deeply and held it aloft in both hands,
    As circular light poured forth and dazzled my eyes.
    Yet foolish as I am, I knew not its name,
    Till the Emperor spoke: "This is the Cloud-Essence
    Of the Nine-Times Refined, where red cinnabar blooms
    And flying vermillion flowers stand as kin.
    Wrapped without in eight stones, within lies gold's heart,
    Infused with the breath of fire and lightning's own fire,
    The soul bound in metal's most potent form.

    "I see how your world wears your mortal frame thin—
    Your nine gates all withered, the six illnesses creeping,
    Your vital essence ebbing away into dusk,
    Until you must wither like grass at year's end.
    Go now, swallow this as you would sweet malt,
    And your face shall grow young as an infant's own bloom.

    I am slow and dull to obey your command—
    But why does Your Majesty grant me this grace?
    This gift from the heavens must not be despised.
    First bathe in the fragrance of orchids sublime,
    Then take it. And not only will it cure my delirium,
    Not only will it bring peace to my wandering mind—
    My teeth and my hair shall rival old P'eng's,
    My body grow light, my temples turn blue,
    And feathers shall sprout in my armpits like silk.
    I'll ride phoenixes paired through the clouds of the sky,
    Ascend to the realm where the immortals dwell,
    And gaze down below at the world of men—
    A mere game played by insects in light.
  footnotes:
    - Nine-Times Refined refers to the Daoist practice of refining cinnabar repeatedly to create the ultimate elixir of immortality.
    - Eight stones refers to eight precious minerals used in Daoist alchemy.
    - Gold's heart (金精) represents the essential power of gold, a key ingredient in alchemical immortality tonics.
    - The nine gates (九竅) are the nine openings of the human body in Chinese medical theory.
    - P'eng (彭祖) was a legendary figure in Chinese mythology said to have lived for over 800 years.
    - The poem satirizes the Daoist pursuit of immortality through alchemy while maintaining the conventions of the courtly dream-vision form.
